            "decision": "PLEASE CALL US IMMEDIATELY FOR ANY OF THE FOLLOWING PROBLEMS:  .  Redness in or drainage from your leg wound(s).  .  New pain, numbness or discoloration of your foot or toes.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 7686,
            "end_offset": 7859,
            "annotation_id": "QM_106"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Watch for signs and symptoms of infection. These are: a fever greater than 101 degrees, chills, increased redness, or pus draining from the incision site. If you experience any of these or bleeding at the incision site, CALL THE DOCTOR",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 7865,
            "end_offset": 8100,
            "annotation_id": "QM_107"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Limit strenuous activity for 6 weeks",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 8120,
            "end_offset": 8156,
            "annotation_id": "QM_108"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Try to keep leg elevated when able",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 8162,
            "end_offset": 8196,
            "annotation_id": "QM_109"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may shower immediately upon coming home. No bathing. A dressing may cover you??????re amputation site and this should be left in place for three (3) days. Remove it after this time and wash your incision(s) gently with soap and water. You will have sutures, which are usually removed in 4 weeks. This will be done by the Surgeon on your follow-up appointment",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 8225,
            "end_offset": 8587,
            "annotation_id": "QM_110"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You will have sutures, which are usually removed in 4 weeks. This will be done by the Surgeon on your follow-up appointment.",
            "category": "Category 6: Therapeutic procedure related",
            "start_offset": 8464,
            "end_offset": 8587,
            "annotation_id": "QM_111"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Sutures / Staples may be removed before discharge. If they are not, an appointment will be made for you to return for staple removal.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 8609,
            "end_offset": 8741,
            "annotation_id": "QM_112"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Sutures / Staples may be removed before discharge. If they are not, an appointment will be made for you to return for staple removal.",
            "category": "Category 6: Therapeutic procedure related",
            "start_offset": 8609,
            "end_offset": 8741,
            "annotation_id": "QM_113"
        },
        {
            "decision": "When the sutures are removed the doctor may or may not place pieces of tape called steri-strips over the incision. ",
            "category": "Category 6: Therapeutic procedure related",
            "start_offset": 8747,
            "end_offset": 8860,
            "annotation_id": "QM_114"
        },
        {
            "decision": "When the sutures are removed the doctor may or may not place pieces of tape called steri-strips over the incision. These will stay on about a week and you may shower with them on. If these do not fall off after 10 days, you may peel them off with warm water and soap in the shower",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 8747,
            "end_offset": 9027,
            "annotation_id": "QM_115"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Avoid taking a tub bath, swimming, or soaking in a hot tub for four weeks after surgery",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 9033,
            "end_offset": 9120,
            "annotation_id": "QM_116"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Unless told otherwise you should resume taking all of the medications you were taking before surgery. You will be given a new prescription for pain medication, which can be taken every three (3) to four (4) hours only if necessary",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 9143,
            "end_offset": 9373,
            "annotation_id": "QM_117"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Unless told otherwise you should resume taking all of the medications you were taking before surgery. You will be given a new prescription for pain medication, which can be taken every three (3) to four (4) hours only if necessary",
            "category": "Category 5: Drug related",
            "start_offset": 9143,
            "end_offset": 9373,
            "annotation_id": "QM_118"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Remember that narcotic pain meds can be constipating ",
            "category": "Category 5: Drug related",
            "start_offset": 9379,
            "end_offset": 9431,
            "annotation_id": "QM_119"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may use over the counter Metamucil or Milk of Magnesia.",
            "category": "Category 5: Drug related",
            "start_offset": 9622,
            "end_offset": 9680,
            "annotation_id": "QM_120"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Remember that narcotic pain meds can be constipating and you should increase the fluid and bulk foods in your diet. (Check with your physician if you have fluid restrictions.) If you feel that you are constipated, do not strain at the toilet. You may use over the counter Metamucil or Milk of Magnesia. Appetite suppression may occur; this will improve with time. Eat small balanced meals throughout the day",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 9379,
            "end_offset": 9786,
            "annotation_id": "QM_121"
        },
        {
            "decision": "NO SMOKING! We know you've heard this before, but it really is an important step to your recovery. Smoking causes narrowing of your blood vessels which in turn decreases circulation. If you smoke you will need to stop as soon as possible. Ask your nurse or doctor for information on smoking cessation",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 9803,
            "end_offset": 10103,
            "annotation_id": "QM_122"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Avoid pressure to your amputation site",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 10109,
            "end_offset": 10147,
            "annotation_id": "QM_123"
        },
        {
            "decision": "No strenuous activity for 6 weeks after surgery",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 10153,
            "end_offset": 10200,
            "annotation_id": "QM_124"
        },
        {
            "decision": "There are no special restrictions on your diet postoperatively. Poor appetite is expected for several weeks and small, frequent meals may be preferred",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 10216,
            "end_offset": 10366,
            "annotation_id": "QM_125"
        },
        {
            "decision": "For people with vascular problems we would recommend a cholesterol lowering diet: Follow a diet low in total fat and low in saturated fat and in cholesterol to improve lipid profile in your blood.",
            "category": "Category 6: Therapeutic procedure related",
            "start_offset": 10372,
            "end_offset": 10567,
            "annotation_id": "QM_126"
        },
        {
            "decision": " Additionally, some people see a reduction in serum cholesterol by reducing dietary cholesterol. Since a reduction in dietary cholesterol is not harmful, we suggest that most people reduce dietary fat, saturated fat and cholesterol to decrease total cholesterol and LDL (Low Density Lipoprotein-the bad cholesterol). ",
            "category": "Category 6: Therapeutic procedure related",
            "start_offset": 10569,
            "end_offset": 10882,
            "annotation_id": "QM_127"
        },
        {
            "decision": "For people with vascular problems we would recommend a cholesterol lowering diet: Follow a diet low in total fat and low in saturated fat and in cholesterol to improve lipid profile in your blood. Additionally, some people see a reduction in serum cholesterol by reducing dietary cholesterol. Since a reduction in dietary cholesterol is not harmful, we suggest that most people reduce dietary fat, saturated fat and cholesterol to decrease total cholesterol and LDL (Low Density Lipoprotein-the bad cholesterol). Exercise will increase your HDL (High Density Lipoprotein-the good cholesterol) and with your doctor's permission, is typically recommended. You may be self-referred or get a referral from your doctor",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 10372,
            "end_offset": 11085,
            "annotation_id": "QM_128"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If you are overweight, you need to think about starting a weight management program. Your health and its improvement depend on it. We know that making changes in your lifestyle will not be easy, and it will require a whole new set of habits and a new attitude. If interested you can may be self-referred or can get a referral from your doctor",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 11091,
            "end_offset": 11433,
            "annotation_id": "QM_129"
        },
        {
            "decision": "diabetes ",
            "category": "Category 3: Defining problem",
            "start_offset": 11451,
            "end_offset": 11459,
            "annotation_id": "QM_130"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If you have diabetes and would like additional guidance, you may request a referral from your doctor",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 11439,
            "end_offset": 11539,
            "annotation_id": "QM_131"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Be sure to keep your medical appointments. The key to your improving health will be to keep a tight reign on any of the chronic medical conditions that you have. Things like high blood pressure, diabetes, and high cholesterol are major villains to the blood vessels. Don't let them go untreated",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 11569,
            "end_offset": 11863,
            "annotation_id": "QM_132"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Please call the office on the first working day after your discharge from the hospital to schedule a follow-up visit. This should be scheduled on the calendar for seven to fourteen days after discharge. Normal office hours are 8:30-5:30 Monday through Friday",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 11869,
            "end_offset": 12127,
            "annotation_id": "QM_133"
        },
        {
            "decision": "PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CALL THE OFFICE WITH ANY OTHER CONCERNS OR QUESTIONS THAT MIGHT ARISE",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12133,
            "end_offset": 12222,
            "annotation_id": "QM_134"
